{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17645965","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17645965"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:23:58+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:23:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18145"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18145","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18145"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.17,0.26,0.17,0.04,0.35]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10859"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73641"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10859","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10859"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18145"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59114"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7331"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25262"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25265"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73641","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/73641"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe intrinsic muscles of the hand are responsible for various movements and functions, including grip strength and fine motor control.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following intrinsic muscles of the hand is primarily responsible for providing power to grip?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Opponens pollicis","Palmar interossei","Adductor pollicis","Abductor pollicis brevis","Palmaris brevis"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eadductor pollicis\u003C/strong\u003E muscle is primarily responsible for providing power to grip. It is an intrinsic muscle of the hand that plays a crucial role in the adduction of the thumb, which is essential for a strong grip.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOpponens pollicis\u003C/strong\u003E - This muscle is involved in the opposition of the thumb, allowing it to touch the other fingers\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPalmar interossei\u003C/strong\u003E - These muscles are involved in adducting the fingers towards the middle finger\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbductor pollicis brevis\u003C/strong\u003E - This muscle is responsible for the abduction of the thumb\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPalmaris brevis\u003C/strong\u003E - This muscle is involved in the movement of the skin on the ulnar side of the palm\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The adductor pollicis muscle is responsible for the powerful grip of the hand.","Intrinsic muscles of the hand are located within the hand itself and are responsible for fine motor movements.","The opponens pollicis muscle is involved in opposition of the thumb, not power grip."],"references":["West, S. G. (2019). Anatomy and physiology of the musculoskeletal system. Rheumatology Secrets E-Book: Rheumatology Secrets E-Book, 17","Miniato MA, Anand P, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Shoulder. 2023 Jul 24. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30725618","Hutson, M., \u0026 Ward, A. (Eds.). (2015). Oxford textbook of musculoskeletal medicine. Oxford University Press","Raszewski JA, Black AC, Launico MV, et al. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Hand Compartments. [Updated 2023 Oct 24]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/sites/books/NBK532942/","McCausland C, Sawyer E, Eovaldi BJ, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Shoulder Muscles. 2023 Aug 8. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30521257","Paulsen, F., \u0026 Waschke, J. (Eds.). (2023). Sobotta Atlas of Anatomy, Vol. 1, English/Latin: General Anatomy and Musculoskeletal System (Vol. 1). Elsevier Health Sciences250"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59114"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18145"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59114","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/59114"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-24T00:59:49+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-13T00:38:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10859"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73641"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"